This one is to all the moms and dads out there… read to the end. 

I don’t know how many times I’ve brushed it off when my mom got all emotional whenever I did something “special” and her saying “you’ll understand once you have a kid”… here I am, 33 and finally able to understand. 

Freyja read a book for me again tonight. She didn’t know how to read the words but she could recall the story story almost word for word just by looking at the pictures. She made voices for each character and even made up an additional character to compliment the story - most of the time the character is either Olaf from frozen or the GRUFFALO. These moments are incredible. It’s might seem small before and after BUT DURING - absolutely amazing. 

I am So proud of her just being herself ❤️

Monday, Tuesday, Friday or Sunday - most days look the same to me. I’ve found that consistency, both in and out of training is key to progress. Making habits out of the right choices is the best way to make sure you are staying on track. 

Accountability, internal or external is a crucial part in process. 

I use the @rpstrength app to keep track and it allows me to also push food around if I know that a meal is going to be “different” from my regular routine. 

I track what I eat - I don’t ALWAYS weight and measure but I do regularly to readjust my “eye”. 

I always eat the same breakfast and 9/10 days my lunch is the same day over day, dinner is usually a rotation of 4-5 dishes.

Breakfast:

2 whole eggs, 200ml egg whites
50g oats
300ml unsweetened almond milk

Lunch:
120g chicken/steak
100g rice
Whole grain wrap
15g peanut butter
Veggies (as much as I can fit)
Half pink lady apple

Dinner: 
Lasagne, burritos, home made burgers, Salmon, bolognese. 

What is your favorite macro friendly dinner?

A healthy relationship with food

What does that mean?  This is a relationship we all GET to have, so let’s make it a happy one

For me it means realizing what it is that I am consuming, knowing what my body needs and making sure I’m “feeding” it accordingly 

It also means ENJOY eating!  It is such a big part of our lives and eating well for you doesn’t have to mean eating boring food and it for sure doesn’t  have to mean eating to little food ! 

I have never had a “bad” relationship when it comes to food.  But I do admit I have had a lack of understanding when it comes to fueling right.  I used to under-eat and I had no idea I just didn’t want to over-eat.  I think it’s important to find a good balance that works for you and that doesn’t have to mean a complicated one because most of the time those don’t last for long.  In my mind it means having knowledge and then making a conscious decision on what is best for you 

I have learned so much of this through the @rpstrength diet APP. Remember, your body can adjust to almost whatever you throw at it, but it doesn’t mean that it will give you 100% back unless you care for it 🤝 

I hope your relationship is a good and happy one ❤️ #rpathlete #training #fuel #eatfood

There is this common misconception that drive and motivation is a constant in all successful people - both in sports and other areas in life. 

I’ll tell you that most days are not like that for me. I am driven to do right by my family, the people who care about me and right by myself. 

Some days that means showing up, doing what you’re supposed to do regardless of how you feel about it. 

Today was one of those days. My head was not in the right place, my hip was hurting and my knees were stiff. But there are certain commitments you cannot run away from - for me that commitment is to do my best at the European CrossFit Games Semifinal and hopefully make it to Madison. For me and for my family. Today I did the work and dissociated the emotions. 

As I walked into kindergarten to pick up my daughter, her smile as she came running towards me confirmed it - she is worth the hard work and I am proud of my effort. THAT is something that is always in my control and one of the best thing I could ever teach her.

Food. And sleep.

One week since I finished my 13th CrossFit Games

I’ve been trying to digest the season the best I can, with all the ups and downs that comes with it. 

I’m proud to compete alongside the 39 other incredible women who made it to @crossfitgames but I’d be lying if I’d say I wasn’t aiming higher. As an athlete, you either win or you grow so I’ll use this opportunity let you in on my experience during the 4 days of competition. 

 
Day 1 is not usually my kind of day, I usually have a slow start and get stronger through the weekend, but with the events on day 1 I felt like I had a very good shot at a great start this year. 

Event 1. I don’t like mass start events but on a bike I feel slightly more comfortable.  I would have preferred a bikeerg but I know I can handle a bike and have confidence in my power output for long time (I Love biking 😄) once I got into lap 3, my legs were feeling heavier than what I would have wanted an the lead pack slowly got away from me. I was disappointed with not staying closer to the top, I knew I had a top 5 in me but I did what I could in the moment. 

Event 2 the pig!! I was excited now - first event jitters were Done! I was ready to GO and I love the 🐷 and was excited to go for it on this event and knew if I stayed close to the front I would catch people on the way back on the pig.  The gymnastics and the wall balls felt great and I managed to pull away from most of the field going into the final 25 chest to bar pull ups. I was second to get to the PIG but on my first flip my calf cramped up and I was forced to abandon my “power clean pull”. The solution was a deadlift, an awkward pull to the shoulder as I split the cramping calf out to the side to avoid excessive use of it. Looking at the clips of this it seemed like I “forgot” how to lift the pig - the result was a slow and painful finish to one of my favorite events. 😳 didn’t see that coming but I sure gave it my all.

Rest in comment

Cross country 5k 

I have been trying to dissect this event since the Games.  I have never run as much as this season. 

I’m a decent runner but I didn’t want it to be a scary event for me.  Running in the heat still in some way gets to me ever since my heatstroke 2015. 

This year I felt as prepared as I have Ever been and I actually had kind of high expectations for the run for the first time. I was so scared but also excited to show my hard work!! 🔥 

I did the first k and felt good, but then it was like something was off.  My legs got heavy and just didn’t feel right.  I did not let it get to me and I continued to push.  I finished slower than I was hoping for and almost 2min min off my best training pace, but looking back I can actually say that I did what I could in the moment. I wasn’t afraid of the heat for the first time and at NO point did my head give up. I still have not fully figured out what happened. Running should be simple, right? Either you’re fast or you’re not. I had shown in training that I can be fast so the outcome was more disappointing than run events in the past..

Yesterday was my first day back to regular training and what better way to start than a 5k TT. I CAN run but guess I need to find a way to manage the pressure.

Calm. 

Calm is a state of tranquility and peacefulness, characterized by a lack of agitation, anxiety, or strong emotions. It's a state of quiet, balanced composure.

At the peak of any game -  in sports or life this is what determines winning or loosing. Being able to focus all of your energy and ability towards the task in front of you is something that should be routinely practiced. 

Even if you have the physical abilities/skill set to “win”, being out of balance will not allow you to access it. 

My best tool to regaining control and finding calm is breath work. I have managed to decrease my resting HR by 3-4 beats by adding in 5min of breath work before bed. I have added 22min of restorative sleep on average my HRV is trending upwards with a 2-3 day delay despite heavy workload. Being able to track these measures almost makes this like a game. And I like games ♥️ #data #whoop #wimhofmethod

Quick poll:
Ladies, do you consider how you eat and fuel during your cycle? 

If you don’t and energy levels and performance remains at the same high level throughout, then GREAT. I couldn’t be happier for you! 

However, for the majority this is not the case and too little guidance is available to help work WITH your physiology instead of AGAINST it. 

The calorie count should still be consistent with your goals (lose weight, maintain, gain weight) but the timing and quantities, especially for athletic performance MATTERS. @rpstrength 

During your high hormone phase (luteal phase, hormones peak 5 days before period) your ability to access glycogen is decreased due to high levels of estrogen and more of your energy will be pulled from fat stores - however this is not great for higher intensity exercise where you need carbohydrates to fuel the anaerobic metabolism. 

Long story short: luteal phase you’ll need to supplement with carbohydrates to maintain blood sugar levels to support high intensity exercise - so you’ll most likely need to move your macros around a little to improve performance and overall wellbeing. #femaleperformance #knowledgeispower #WomenAreNotSmallMen

HEART RATE, WEIGHTS above 85% of max and SLEEP might be the key to staying YOU for as long as possible!

Most of the current recommendations for women when they age do little to actually counter-act the changes that are happening in the body. Loss of muscle mass, loss of bone density, and lower energy levels are part of life but there are LOTS we can do to delay the process for as long as possible. 

INTENSITY AND LOAD is the KEY

Plain and simple, when women grow older (peri and post menopause) the hormones are no longer in balance and the decrease in estrogen and progesterone production will cause bodywide changes - both physically and mentally. 

HOWEVER, by dosing in High Intensity Interval Training and heavy loading, you can assist the dwindling hormone levels with sending stimulus to the brain, muscle and bones that it is all still needed! 

High intensity, heavy loads and rock solid sleep is the best way to be at your best as menopause is approaching and beyond. 

Track your cycle, your daily strain and most importantly your SLEEP. Being able to track and monitor your sleep is the best way to make sure you are setting yourself up for a “successful” nights sleep! Video @arninn95

WHO NEEDS MORE PROTEIN??

There is a common misconception that men need more protein than women. It might be true in absolute terms if there is more muscle mass to support, but something that is often overlooked is how the female body responds to the ingested protein and the quantities. 

Women actually need larger doses of protein post training to avoid staying in a catabolic state (muscle breakdown) after training than men. To trigger the rebuild response current research suggests that we need higher amounts of leucine, so ladies, get yourself an extra large scoop - the one in the bag is for men, so let’s start double dipping. 

Rule of thumb:

30 year old = 30g protein
Menopause = 40g protein

The whole “eating for two” is not technically correct, but your hormones are for sure making your stomach feel like you need to!

Cravings are REAL, and so is the struggle to keep out of the pantry. Sometimes I’m successful - other times not so much. 

However, I always try to tell myself that the quick fix is NOT the right solution. 

The fluctuations of estrogen and progesterone plays a trick on you and can drastically change the levels of and sensitivity to grehlin and leptin, two hormones closely controlling the feeling of hunger. 

Exercise is one of the best way to combat grehlin and gain control of your eating. Fiber as well as plenty of fluids is another great tool to keep yourself out of the pantry and on track @rpstrength 

This is also the case if you’re on your own (not with an extra person inside of you 😊)

“Do what you are used to doing” during pregnancy I absolutely love this advice.  However take to with a grain of salt for myself.  As a professional athlete, we are pushing our physical boundaries to gain an edge all the time. 

Normally I try to silence my mind and allow the physical pain to persist, but during pregnancy I listen to my body as there are hormonal and physical changes that makes it hard for me to know what is “good” pain and what is “bad” pain. 

I am not trying to get stronger and I am not trying to get fitter…. I am maintaining good conditioning and strength as much as I can.  I ALWAYS monitor my heart rate when I do conditioning and it allows me to stay below my threshold where there is a hypothetical risk of very low oxygen saturation. (That helps ME find MY boundary) 

I’ve found that periods without training drains me more than it recharges me - so I focus on what I CAN do and make sure to tell myself that being active will be good for me and my baby - both now and later. I still train twice a day most days and it makes me feel good and strong 🤝🙏

#strong #training #mom #pregnant #enjoylife #momentous

Christmas tradition that we do every year ❤️🎄

The making of laufabrauð 
(Icelandic tradition since the settlers, a little hard to make but don’t feel like it’s Christmas without it)

500g wheat
35g butter
15g sugar
250-260g full milk
1 teaspoon baking powder 

I add in a pinch of salt

Add all dry ingredients together 
Add butter squeeze in with hands into the mix 
Luke warm milk that you add in VERY slowly while mixing 

Roll into a sausage roll about 3 inches (keep in moist tea towel while rolling out each pancake so the dough won’t dry up) cut each roll into 15-20 pieces and roll out thin

Decorate as you want to by carving out!!! 🤩

Make sure to puncture small holes into them after you finish so they won’t all bubble up when you cook 🧑‍🍳 

Fry in oil when all cakes are ready 

Enjoy with Christmas meal with dipping into some butter 🫶

Body image is a b**ch…. So many feelings, thoughts and doubts - regardless of whether you are a competitive athlete or not. 

I KNOW, and I would tell others, you are who you are and your body is incredible for what it does and gives you, regardless of what it looks like!! 

However it can be hard every once in a while to do what you preach, but i will take that challenge and do my best to live by it. 

The beginning of pregnancy where you start showing but you are still “hiding it” till it’s safe to announce, is HARD. Once you announce, you continue to grow, you still feel “soft” and somewhat out of shape, but the feeling of carrying life is incredible ❤️ 

women show at different times, all of us are different and each pregnancy might be different as well. 
This time I started showing a lot earlier and growing a lot faster.  I wore loose shirts but it also doesn’t feel like ME.  It wasn’t until my belly was a little bigger and the loose shirts weren’t hiding anything anyways I decided to just not care.  Wear what I am comfortable in and do ME.  It’s not always easy but maaan it feels a lot better to be free 

17 weeks and this is what my power belly looks like! Grateful 🫶 and also thankful for my health and being able to continue to train and lift weights 🏋️‍♀️

How well do you know Mr. Cortisol?

Mr. Cortisol is Not a bad guy, but if you fill up the room with guys like him, he will definitely bring down the house. 

An unbalanced diet can be a massive stress on your body and this can lead to high cortisol levels. This, in combination with other internal and external stressors can overload the system.

1.	Weakened immune system: Prolonged high cortisol can suppress the immune system, making the body more susceptible to infections.

2.	Weight gain: Elevated cortisol levels may contribute to increased abdominal fat, as cortisol influences fat storage and metabolism.

3.	Imbalanced blood sugar: Cortisol can affect insulin sensitivity, potentially leading to imbalances in blood sugar levels.

4.	Digestive issues: High cortisol may contribute to digestive problems, such as slowed metabolism and nutrient absorption.

5.	Sleep disturbances: Cortisol disruptions can interfere with the sleep-wake cycle, leading to difficulties falling asleep or staying asleep.

6.	Cognitive issues: Prolonged stress and high cortisol levels may impact memory, concentration, and overall cognitive function.

7.	Hormonal imbalances: Cortisol can influence other hormones, potentially disrupting reproductive hormones and menstrual cycles.

8.	Cardiovascular issues: Chronic stress and elevated cortisol levels may contribute to hypertension and increased risk of cardiovascular diseases.

Don’t STRESS about this!!! To summarize, EAT enough to support your body, a well fueled machine will handle a rougher drive - and you get to do the things you want. @rpstrength
